{"term":"2000","caseName":"Daniels v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2000/99-9136","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 08, 2001","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/rehnquist10/oral_argument_audio/23094","transcript":[{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument now in Number 99-9136, Earthy Daniels v. United States.","start":0,"stop":8.132,"duration":8.13},{"text":"Mr. Tanaka.","start":8.132,"stop":9.528,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":9.528,"stop":12.606,"duration":3.08},{"text":"Mr. Daniels was convicted of being an ex-felon in possession of a firearm.","start":12.606,"stop":16.694,"duration":4.09},{"text":"Normally, that charge carries a maximum term of 10 years.","start":16.694,"stop":21.516,"duration":4.82},{"text":"Where, however, the person has suffered three qualifying felonies, that term, maximum term goes up to life, and there's a mandatory minimum term of 15 years, which Mr. Daniels was sentenced to.","start":21.516,"stop":33.147,"duration":11.63},{"text":"Where those convictions are both unconstitutional and unreliable, the resulting sentence is likewise unconstitutional, and the issue before this case is whether section 2255 provides a forum and remedy to address that unconstitutionality of the sentence.","start":33.147,"stop":51.217,"duration":18.07}]},{"speakerName":"Sandra Day O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask whether the record shows whether the petitioner challenged those '78 and '81 convictions in a timely manner on direct appeal at the State and/or Federal level?","start":51.217,"stop":64.566,"duration":13.35}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe that's in the record.","start":64.566,"stop":66.446,"duration":1.88},{"text":"There is no indication that he has challenged those at the State level.","start":66.446,"stop":71.248,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"Sandra Day O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"You know, it seems to me that the opportunity to make those challenges very likely occurred when the convictions became final.","start":71.248,"stop":82.34,"duration":11.09}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true, Your Honor, and I'm sure that there was, in California, a procedure for direct appeal and, lacking that, also collateral review of those convictions, but that's not what's at issue today.","start":82.34,"stop":93.018,"duration":10.68},{"text":"At issue today is its use in the Federal sentencing procedure, so--","start":93.018,"stop":97.359,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why shouldn't there be a measure of finality here?","start":97.359,"stop":100.902,"duration":3.54},{"text":"I mean, you know, you can go back and argue was it constitutional, was it accurate, but also there's an interest in getting things done within a certain time frame.","start":100.902,"stop":110.239,"duration":9.34}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--I agree, Your Honor, and there... but there is finality with respect to those State convictions.","start":110.239,"stop":117.119,"duration":6.88},{"text":"The State of California, he served those convictions, he served the prior terms, he served his imprisonment.","start":117.119,"stop":122.8,"duration":5.68},{"text":"Those convictions are final as to the California judgment.","start":122.8,"stop":125.872,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Sandra Day O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, are there statutes of limitations for habeas actions as well?","start":125.872,"stop":129.62,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly there are.","start":129.62,"stop":130.497,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Sandra Day O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"And that being the case, this is an end run around those, it seems to me.","start":130.497,"stop":137.102,"duration":6.6}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't believe so, Justice O'Connor.","start":137.102,"stop":139.485,"duration":2.38},{"text":"The statute of limitation goes to the underlying conviction, and certainly he had his chance to challenge those, and that time has long since passed, and we're not challenging that judgment, that conviction, but when that conviction is used, again, to increase his Federal sentence, then necessarily the Federal court must look at its reliability, otherwise it's a violation of due process.","start":139.485,"stop":165.391,"duration":25.91}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Tanaka, even if you're right that there's no bar from challenging the Federal, the abuse in the Federal proceeding, shouldn't the Federal court at least take into account, in determining whether 2255 really is warranted, that these matters could have been raised earlier in the State proceedings on direct appeal or on collateral attack?","start":165.391,"stop":192.261,"duration":26.87}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't believe so, Your Honor.","start":192.261,"stop":193.929,"duration":1.67},{"text":"Again, the Federal interest is totally different than the State interest.","start":193.929,"stop":200.048,"duration":6.12},{"text":"The State has no--","start":200.048,"stop":201.622,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Why shouldn't the Federal interest include did this person have a reason for not bringing this up earlier?","start":201.622,"stop":211.314,"duration":9.69},{"text":"I mean, one can imagine cases where you might try to knock out for Federal sentencing purposes an earlier State conviction and say, there was a procedural impediment, or there was a reason I didn't know about this until much later, like Brady material that wasn't turned over?","start":211.314,"stop":231.462,"duration":20.15},{"text":"Shouldn't there be at least that requirement, that for the 2255 purpose you would have to show a good reason for not raising it earlier in the State courts?","start":231.462,"stop":242.537,"duration":11.08}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--I agree that that would explain, and there certainly would be cases where that would explain why it wasn't raised, and that perhaps presents a more compelling case, but I don't think it's a prerequisite, and the reason for that is--","start":242.537,"stop":256.846,"duration":14.31}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But you're... but I wanted just to be clear on one thing.","start":256.846,"stop":259.051,"duration":2.2},{"text":"You're not saying in this case that there was any special reason why these matters could not have been raised earlier?","start":259.051,"stop":267.179,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's correct, I'm not making any claim that he was prevented by something external to himself that prevented him from raising this in State court, but I don't think the argument depends on that.","start":267.179,"stop":277.563,"duration":10.38},{"text":"Again--","start":277.563,"stop":277.936,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You said a few times that the... this is just a Federal matter, it's final as far as the law of the State is concerned.","start":277.936,"stop":284.226,"duration":6.29},{"text":"Does the State of California have an interest in the integrity that's accorded to its judgments in this proceeding?","start":284.226,"stop":290.179,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--The State of California has an interest in the integrity of its judgments.","start":290.179,"stop":295.949,"duration":5.77},{"text":"Where... and I guess the State of California has some perhaps minimal interest in whether its judgment is used conclusively as a Federal sentencing predicate.","start":295.949,"stop":310.189,"duration":14.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it would have a very strong interest.","start":310.189,"stop":312.584,"duration":2.39},{"text":"It has its own three-strikes rule, as I understand, and is this man a resident of the State of California?","start":312.584,"stop":319.946,"duration":7.36},{"text":"I assume he is.","start":319.946,"stop":320.913,"duration":0.97},{"text":"It seems to me it has a very strong interest in having its judgments of criminal convictions respected.","start":320.913,"stop":327.886,"duration":6.97}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we--","start":327.886,"stop":328.778,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And to say that, oh, this is just a Federal matter, it's final so far as the law of the State is concerned, I'm not sure is a complete answer.","start":328.778,"stop":334.768,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, it is respected in the sense that it has a presumptive validity, and certainly this Court's case in Custis established that fact, and no one's suggesting that we go behind that validity once it's presented, but there's... I don't know that it has an interest in a conclusive-type validity, especially where it's being used as a Federal sentencing predicate.","start":334.768,"stop":361.688,"duration":26.92},{"text":"Now--","start":361.688,"stop":362.009,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, supposing that there's a thought, you win on your ability to challenge, and it's thought there's necessary to be a evidentiary hearing.","start":362.009,"stop":371.283,"duration":9.27},{"text":"What incentive does the State have at that point to come in and try to show that the conviction was properly obtained?","start":371.283,"stop":377.604,"duration":6.32}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't know that the State would necessarily be a party.","start":377.604,"stop":381.095,"duration":3.49},{"text":"I don't believe they have very much incentive--","start":381.095,"stop":383.311,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Then it's a very strange proceeding.","start":383.311,"stop":384.879,"duration":1.57},{"text":"You're challenging the judgment of a State, and yet the State isn't a party?","start":384.879,"stop":384.879,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--But it's the Federal Government that's seeking to use that judgment as a Federal sentencing predicate to increase the Federal sentence in Federal court.","start":384.879,"stop":399.288,"duration":14.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And if you prevail and you go ahead and have the judgment declared invalid, I... what would happen if the State in a subsequent proceeding tried to use those convictions for its own three-strikes rule?","start":399.288,"stop":414.347,"duration":15.06}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"I would assume that the State could validly use those convictions in its own three-strike rule, because the Federal sentence, the Federal procedure would just invalidate the State conviction, or the use of the State conviction, not the State conviction itself, as a means to lengthen the Federal sentence.","start":414.347,"stop":431.271,"duration":16.92},{"text":"The--","start":431.271,"stop":431.987,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if the State uses the conviction, it's... the conviction is just as unreliable when the State uses it as when the Feds use it, and I take it the reason that you concede that the State could use it is that there was an understanding, or we have to assume that there was an understanding on the part of the prisoner that this kind of collateral use and enhancement of later sentences might be a consequence of that conviction, and yet he did nothing about it.","start":431.987,"stop":475.645,"duration":43.66},{"text":"Is that essentially your theory?","start":475.645,"stop":464.969,"duration":-10.68},{"text":"In other words, he knew what the risks were, and he did not take any steps to alleviate those risks by bringing a State collateral attack or by going on with his appeal or whatnot.","start":464.969,"stop":476.914,"duration":11.94}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--Certainly that's part of it, but the... now the--","start":476.914,"stop":479.331,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why doesn't... I'm sorry.","start":479.331,"stop":480.551,"duration":1.22},{"text":"Go ahead.","start":480.551,"stop":481.038,"duration":0.49},{"text":"You... That was part of it.","start":481.038,"stop":483.149,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, I agree--","start":483.149,"stop":483.333,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the other part?","start":483.333,"stop":484.034,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the other part would be that the State would obviously not be bound by anything that happened in the Federal proceeding.","start":484.034,"stop":491.884,"duration":7.85}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no, but let's forget Federal proceedings for a moment.","start":491.884,"stop":494.696,"duration":2.81},{"text":"If we just have a State proceeding and the State is going to use that supposedly unreliable conviction as a basis for enhancement following a subsequent conviction, nothing unfair about that, I take it, on your view, because the prisoner knew that such use could be made of it, and the prisoner let the time for attacking the conviction pass.","start":494.696,"stop":518.277,"duration":23.58},{"text":"That's essentially your theory?","start":518.277,"stop":520.135,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"That could well be.","start":520.135,"stop":520.839,"duration":0.7},{"text":"There could well be due process problems associated with its subsequent use in the State, but it might be that those problems are--","start":520.839,"stop":529.171,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what are they?","start":529.171,"stop":529.417,"duration":0.25},{"text":"I mean, I... if it's not unfair for the State to use it, despite the assumption of its unreliability, what would a... what other due process problem might arise at the State level?","start":529.417,"stop":544.117,"duration":14.7}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--That would be the problem.","start":544.117,"stop":545.383,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be the problem, and--","start":545.383,"stop":546.486,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"But it might be that the problem doesn't rise to a large enough level that the State necessarily violates due process by refusing to litigate that anew.","start":546.486,"stop":555.617,"duration":9.13},{"text":"In other words--","start":555.617,"stop":556.857,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the State... but I... the theory of my question was, he in effect was on notice that there might be a subsequent use of the conviction for enhancement purposes.","start":556.857,"stop":566.691,"duration":9.83},{"text":"He had an opportunity to litigate.","start":566.691,"stop":569.013,"duration":2.32},{"text":"He didn't litigate. Therefore, it is not unfair, in the due process sense, for the State to use it, and I thought that was probably what underlay your suggestion that the State could use it for enhancement purposes.","start":569.013,"stop":582.963,"duration":13.95}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--I agree with that.","start":582.963,"stop":583.934,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":583.934,"stop":584.405,"duration":0.47},{"text":"Now, why can't the Fed... why can't a Federal court use it for enhancement purposes?","start":584.405,"stop":589.229,"duration":4.82},{"text":"He was on notice that there might be a later enhancement.","start":589.229,"stop":593.074,"duration":3.84},{"text":"He did nothing about it.","start":593.074,"stop":594.496,"duration":1.42},{"text":"The same reasoning applies at the Federal level, doesn't it?","start":594.496,"stop":597.383,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"The... there is a... there is no problem with notice, and... but that again suggests the concept of waiver, or maybe even sandbagging.","start":597.383,"stop":607.31,"duration":9.93}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, not waiver.","start":607.31,"stop":608.664,"duration":1.35},{"text":"Not... we're not talking about waiver.","start":608.664,"stop":610.735,"duration":2.07},{"text":"We talking about, I think, the fact that he had an opportunity to litigate it.","start":610.735,"stop":616.798,"duration":6.06},{"text":"As you so... as you conceded a moment ago, there are statutes of limitations that govern these things in most instances.","start":616.798,"stop":624.288,"duration":7.49},{"text":"You've got to litigate within that time or it's too late, so he let, in effect, his opportunity to litigate pass.","start":624.288,"stop":632.545,"duration":8.26},{"text":"Now, if that... and therefore it's not unfair, in a due process sense, to use it against him even if he does claim later that it was unreliable.","start":632.545,"stop":641.627,"duration":9.08},{"text":"Now, if that is a sound argument with respect to its use for enhancement purposes at the State level, why isn't it an equally good argument with respect to its use in this case at the Federal level?","start":641.627,"stop":654.183,"duration":12.56}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, perhaps I didn't understand the predicate of your question when I first answered.","start":654.183,"stop":658.746,"duration":4.56},{"text":"I believe I answered that there is a due process problem with using the unreliable conviction whether you're using it to enhance a State sentence or a Federal sentence.","start":658.746,"stop":668.107,"duration":9.36}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Then what's left of the statute of limitations that you concede can be applied?","start":668.107,"stop":672.572,"duration":4.47},{"text":"I thought you conceded that the statute of limitations on this kind of litigation could, consistently with due process, be applied at the State level.","start":672.572,"stop":686.58,"duration":14.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If you did not concede that, then I will withdraw my question.","start":686.58,"stop":690.888,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":690.888,"stop":691.118,"duration":0.23},{"text":"It could be applied at the State level to the initial State conviction.","start":691.118,"stop":694.52,"duration":3.4},{"text":"Okay, again, if, analogous to this case, that conviction was used in a State proceeding to enhance a subsequent State sentence, then there might... there would be a due process right to examine that conviction anew--","start":694.52,"stop":711.874,"duration":17.35}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you--","start":711.874,"stop":712.908,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--with respect to the enhancement provision--","start":712.908,"stop":714.991,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--With respect to, at the State level, let me ask you one more question.","start":714.991,"stop":716.866,"duration":1.88},{"text":"Let's assume that the State had a statute and the statute were made... was explained to the defendant at the time of his State sentence, and the statute read as follows:","start":716.866,"stop":730.868,"duration":14},{"text":"This conviction can be used to enhance sentences following later convictions.","start":730.868,"stop":739.937,"duration":9.07},{"text":"If you wish to challenge the validity of this conviction, you must challenge it within 1 year, or it's too late.","start":739.937,"stop":748.47,"duration":8.53},{"text":"Let's assume that the State had such a statute, that was explained to the prisoner at the time of the first sentence, and he didn't litigate within 1 year.","start":748.47,"stop":758.836,"duration":10.37},{"text":"The State then wants to use it to enhance following a subsequent conviction.","start":758.836,"stop":764.08,"duration":5.24},{"text":"Is there a due process problem in the State's use of it without an opportunity to challenge?","start":764.08,"stop":769.272,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--There well could be, if there's some unreliability of the conviction.","start":769.272,"stop":773.538,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"So there can... I take it your theory, then, is that no amount of warning in the world will ever be enough to allow the State or the Federal Government to treat the first conviction with finality?","start":773.538,"stop":789.019,"duration":15.48}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":789.019,"stop":791.839,"duration":2.82},{"text":"There... as long as there's a procedure, a substantive due process procedure for litigating that, it could be that, consistent with due process, there could be some limitations and in that case that might well be one of them.","start":791.839,"stop":807.911,"duration":16.07}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what about my limitation?","start":807.911,"stop":808.556,"duration":0.65},{"text":"You've got a year to challenge this if you want to challenge it, and if you don't challenge it within the year it's too late and it can used for enhancement purposes, and the year expires, it's going to be used for enhancement purposes, he wants to challenge it, and the State says no, it's too late, the year is over.","start":808.556,"stop":825.702,"duration":17.15},{"text":"Is that consistent with due process?","start":825.702,"stop":827.203,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it well could be.","start":827.203,"stop":828.067,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":828.067,"stop":828.572,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume that your theory would apply not just to enhancement questions but also to any other disabilities attaching to the prior criminal conviction.","start":828.572,"stop":841.796,"duration":13.22},{"text":"Specifically, I believe that California, like many States, disqualifies convicted felons from voting.","start":841.796,"stop":851.916,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Now, could your client have presented himself at the registration booth for voting and, when told that he could not vote because he was a felon, could he say, oh, but that conviction was invalid and I want an opportunity to challenge it?","start":851.916,"stop":871.88,"duration":19.96}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't believe so, Your Honor.","start":871.88,"stop":873.418,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Why not?","start":873.418,"stop":851.916,"duration":-21.5}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"The difference is this.","start":874.262,"stop":851.916,"duration":-22.35},{"text":"In this case... due process is obviously a flexible concept, and what's at stake here is 1) an automatic increase in the sentence and 2) a dramatic increase in the sentence.","start":851.916,"stop":888.849,"duration":36.93},{"text":"The sentence went from presumptively 7 years to more than double, to a min... to a minimum of 15 years.","start":888.849,"stop":894.624,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"The right to vote is worth something, too. We protect that with many due process and other restrictions upon what the State can do.","start":894.624,"stop":908.656,"duration":14.03},{"text":"Why shouldn't he have the right to... you're saying you cannot use the conviction for anything except sending him to jail upon the first conviction.","start":908.656,"stop":923.95,"duration":15.29},{"text":"If you say you can't use it to increase his sentence on the later conviction, I don't see why you also don't have to say you can't use it to disable him from voting.","start":923.95,"stop":935.274,"duration":11.32}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I think there's certainly a greater liberty interest with respect to imprisonment, but--","start":935.274,"stop":939.899,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Tanaka, in your last series of answers you seem to be departing from what I thought was the clear line you took in your brief.","start":939.899,"stop":951.636,"duration":11.74},{"text":"That is, for all State purposes you are accepting that this sentence is good, and you are distinguishing the Federal enhancement from any other... from any State law consequence, but now in your answer to the questions that Justice Souter and Justice Scalia just asked you seem to be saying it's not just the Federal enhancement purpose that you're questioning where this can be brought up but also in the State proceeding as well.","start":951.636,"stop":986.844,"duration":35.21}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, I don't believe so.","start":986.844,"stop":988.626,"duration":1.78},{"text":"Obviously the only fact at issue here is the... is its use in the Federal proceeding, and--","start":988.626,"stop":997.578,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"You kept saying in your brief that you're not touching the State consequences of this, that those are a given, and you accept those, but your answers here depart from that view, so which is it?","start":997.578,"stop":1010.142,"duration":12.56}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'll stick with what I said in the brief.","start":1010.142,"stop":1012.893,"duration":2.75},{"text":"We're not challenging any State use of this conviction.","start":1012.893,"stop":1017.042,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But we're trying to understand why that should be.","start":1017.042,"stop":1018.837,"duration":1.79},{"text":"I... my understanding of your submission is that there is a Federal constitutional right under the Due Process Clause not to have this conviction used in Federal court.","start":1018.837,"stop":1029.041,"duration":10.2},{"text":"Why is... why don't you make the same argument if it's a State three strike conviction case?","start":1029.041,"stop":1033.948,"duration":4.91}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"One might--","start":1033.948,"stop":1035.565,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a Federal due process right not to have what you call an unreliable or a false conviction used... again, it's the same analysis, same Constitution.","start":1035.565,"stop":1045.662,"duration":10.1},{"text":"What's the difference?","start":1045.662,"stop":1047.316,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--And one might, if one were arguing that case, argue that, and I think there... but there are certainly different considerations there, because if the Federal court is reviewing the State court's use of its own recidivist provisions, then there are more comity and finality questions that aren't at issue here.","start":1047.316,"stop":1066.206,"duration":18.89},{"text":"That's what distinguishes this case, is that all we're doing in this case is looking at the Federal court examining a Federal sentence under 2255, which explicitly provides for that review.","start":1066.206,"stop":1077.616,"duration":11.41},{"text":"There's no intrusion in the State court judgment, and that's the position I took in the brief and that's the position I take here, that the State judgment, we're leaving that alone.","start":1077.616,"stop":1089.819,"duration":12.2},{"text":"Nothing that the Federal district court's going to do in granting that 2255 motion and finding this conviction too unreliable to automatically sentence this man to an additional 8 years in prison is going to affect that State court judgment.","start":1089.819,"stop":1104.331,"duration":14.51}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm trying to have... my problem is... I agree with you basically.","start":1104.331,"stop":1107.741,"duration":3.41},{"text":"You realize that these things should be challengeable in a sentencing proceeding.","start":1107.741,"stop":1112.406,"duration":4.66},{"text":"I wrote an opinion to that effect in Palleo, and it was reversed by this Court, so now what do I do?","start":1112.406,"stop":1120.022,"duration":7.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laughter]","start":1120.022,"stop":1120.369,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you use your--","start":1120.369,"stop":1125.251,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, my problem is, quite honestly, that I don't see any way, if you're not... I think these things... I think a prior should be challengeable in the sentencing hearing, all right?","start":1125.251,"stop":1131.278,"duration":6.03},{"text":"That's clear, simple, done all the time, no problem, fair.","start":1131.278,"stop":1134.873,"duration":3.6},{"text":"All right.","start":1134.873,"stop":1135.483,"duration":0.61},{"text":"No, but there's an opinion that says no.","start":1135.483,"stop":1138.042,"duration":2.56},{"text":"Now, given that opinion, I think I'm stuck, unless I were to accept this argument that the... I see you make an argument about the constitutionality, which I think is interesting, but I'm not sure about that one.","start":1138.042,"stop":1152.811,"duration":14.77},{"text":"Is there anything else?","start":1152.811,"stop":1154.259,"duration":1.45},{"text":"If I don't accept that constitutional point, if I would have been with the dissenters in Custis... but I believe in stare decisis.","start":1154.259,"stop":1162.616,"duration":8.36},{"text":"I'm stuck, right?","start":1162.616,"stop":1164.114,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, if you don't accept that constitutional point that the use of an unreliable prior conviction that doesn't implicate the person... doesn't implicate the person's guilt can be automatically used to dramatically increase the sentence conclusively, then we're both stuck, unless you can use your powers of persuasion to change the Court's decision, but--","start":1164.114,"stop":1189.912,"duration":25.8},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":1189.912,"stop":1190.106,"duration":0.19},{"text":"That's certainly the genesis of this argument.","start":1190.106,"stop":1194.144,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I just ask one question?","start":1194.144,"stop":1200.786,"duration":6.64},{"text":"Are you really making a constitutional argument, or are you arguing for a construction of section 2255, or is it both?","start":1200.786,"stop":1208.441,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"It's both.","start":1208.441,"stop":1211.022,"duration":2.58},{"text":"Certainly the case depends on a construction of 2255 to remedy what is an obvious constitutional violation.","start":1211.022,"stop":1219.869,"duration":8.85},{"text":"By its plain language, 2255 allows someone sentenced in Federal court to challenge that sentence as being unconstitutional, and it gives the sentencing court the power to correct that sentence as, in fact, a constitutional--","start":1219.869,"stop":1233.199,"duration":13.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But does your position have to rest on the premise that the sentence would be unconstitutional if the State conviction were... that the Federal sentence would be unconstitutional if the State sentence were invalid?","start":1233.199,"stop":1233.199,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--Not just invalid--","start":1233.199,"stop":1246.49,"duration":13.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You see, it seems to me it would be theoretically possible to say, for a legislature to say, we wanted to enhance a sentence if there's a State conviction out there, and we don't care whether it's obtained fairly or not.","start":1246.49,"stop":1256.87,"duration":10.38},{"text":"The fellow was at least indicted and he went to jail for a while, and that's enough for us.","start":1256.87,"stop":1260.507,"duration":3.64},{"text":"Is it your view that they could not do that?","start":1260.507,"stop":1262.972,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1262.972,"stop":1263.768,"duration":0.8},{"text":"Where it can be shown that that conviction doesn't reliably indicate the man's guilt I believe... well, it's my position that that violates the Constitution and the Due Process Clause.","start":1263.768,"stop":1272.722,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Tanaka, I have a question concerning a point you made in your brief.","start":1272.722,"stop":1280.428,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"You said that the 2255 forum is accustomed to dealing with questions of this nature, and you distinguished that from the sentencing forum in Custis, but it seems to me it's the same forum.","start":1280.428,"stop":1294.366,"duration":13.94},{"text":"It's the same district judge, just a different proceeding but in the same court, so I did not follow what you were getting at when you were saying that the 2255 forum is accustomed to dealing with these kinds of questions but the sentencing judge is not, when it's one and the same judge.","start":1294.366,"stop":1313.626,"duration":19.26}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the point was that normally a sentencing procedure is rather quick and summary, whereas a proceeding on a 2255 case, there might be an evidentiary hearing and the scheduling and so forth would be different, and also there are rules that govern 2255 cases that don't govern sentencing, and so it's more appropriately placed there.","start":1313.626,"stop":1336.678,"duration":23.05},{"text":"But the major point is that 2255 expressly provides for this type of procedure, whereas you know, obviously there's nothing in the sentencing statute that likely, likewise provides for it.","start":1336.678,"stop":1351.956,"duration":15.28}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Tanaka, you say that what you want to challenge is State court convictions that, judgments that do not reliably indicate guilt.","start":1351.956,"stop":1361.058,"duration":9.1},{"text":"Well, I take it you would allow a challenge on the basis that a Miranda warning wasn't given, and that there was some... it was not harmless error, and yet a Miranda warning really has nothing to do with guilt.","start":1361.058,"stop":1375.872,"duration":14.81},{"text":"I mean, there are certainly different constitutional claims which can be vindicated in the proper forum but don't really bear on guilt or innocence, so are you limiting your challenges to those which clearly affect guilt, or to any constitutional claim that would be sustained if timely brought?","start":1375.872,"stop":1392.669,"duration":16.8}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1392.669,"stop":1393.952,"duration":1.28},{"text":"I believe that the due process analysis leads to the conclusion that you can only challenge convictions that don't reliably indicate guilt.","start":1393.952,"stop":1403.236,"duration":9.28},{"text":"There's not an identity between a due process violation and a constitutional violation.","start":1403.236,"stop":1410.845,"duration":7.61},{"text":"If the Court has no further questions, I'd like to reserve the remainder of my time for rebuttal.","start":1410.845,"stop":1415.212,"duration":4.37}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well, Mr. Tanaka.","start":1415.212,"stop":1416.194,"duration":0.98},{"text":"Mr. Dreeben, we'll hear from you.","start":1416.194,"stop":1419.539,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1419.539,"stop":1423.06,"duration":3.52},{"text":"In Custis v. United States this Court made clear that at a Federal sentencing proceeding a defendant who faces recidivist sentencing may not bring a constitutional challenge to the validity of the underlying enhancement conviction.","start":1423.06,"stop":1438.293,"duration":15.23},{"text":"We submit that the same principle applies where it--","start":1438.293,"stop":1442.52,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"With certain exceptions.","start":1442.52,"stop":1443.125,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--With the exception of a conviction that was entered in violation of Gideon v. Wainwright, that's correct, Justice Stevens.","start":1443.125,"stop":1449.631,"duration":6.51}]},{"speakerName":"Sandra Day O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"You think that's the only such exception?","start":1449.631,"stop":1451.941,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that that is the line that the Court drew in Custis, Justice O'Connor.","start":1451.941,"stop":1456.804,"duration":4.86},{"text":"It rested that on a variety of considerations.","start":1456.804,"stop":1459.922,"duration":3.12},{"text":"The first was that the Court's jurisprudence had recognized Gideon violations as a unique constitutional defect that rose even to the level of a jurisdictional defect.","start":1459.922,"stop":1469.672,"duration":9.75},{"text":"The second two reasons I think are the ones that most clearly explain the rule that we're espousing here.","start":1469.672,"stop":1477.357,"duration":7.68}]},{"speakerName":"Sandra Day O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how about a so called Brady violation, where the facts aren't known until maybe immediately before the sentencing proceeding in the new crime?","start":1477.357,"stop":1488.861,"duration":11.5}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are two distinctions between that kind of a situation and the Gideon situation.","start":1488.861,"stop":1495.191,"duration":6.33},{"text":"The one that I think is most applicable to the majority of cases that are going to come up in this context is that a Brady violation is a very fact intensive inquiry.","start":1495.191,"stop":1504.62,"duration":9.43},{"text":"It can't be resolved, as the Court noted in Custis with respect to a Gideon claim, simply by looking at the judgment or the judgment role and determining whether the defendant had counsel.","start":1504.62,"stop":1514.366,"duration":9.75},{"text":"It requires instead a fairly intricate analysis of whether the Government suppressed and withheld information that the defendant couldn't with due diligence have gained access to, and whether there was resulting prejudice to the defendant as a consequence, and the administrative costs of adjudicating that are far more substantial and very intrusive into the sentencing process as compared to Gideon.","start":1514.366,"stop":1536.998,"duration":22.63}]},{"speakerName":"Sandra Day O'Connor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what about a DNA claim in a death case coming up later?","start":1536.998,"stop":1542.057,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the second... I think, Justice O'Connor, that is the second distinction in your hypothetical, that the hypothetical posits that this was information about a constitutional claim that could not with due diligence have been obtained, I'm assuming within any time for bringing an appropriate appeal or collateral challenge.","start":1542.057,"stop":1560.572,"duration":18.51},{"text":"The capital context is unique in that area, I think, and I'm going to set it aside, because questions of actual innocence in the capital context would be dealt with under the Eighth Amendment and would implicate constitutional principles that aren't broadly applicable.","start":1560.572,"stop":1576.663,"duration":16.09},{"text":"But as to the generality of sentencing cases, I think that the basic rule is that there is a system in place to challenge convictions that balances two fundamental interests.","start":1576.663,"stop":1589.489,"duration":12.83},{"text":"One is in finality, the other is in fundamental fairness.","start":1589.489,"stop":1594.095,"duration":4.61},{"text":"Those two interests have always been accommodated not by giving one total sway over the other, but by saying that in certain contexts there are claims that are available and they may be brought, and if they are brought in a manner that's compatible with the procedural limitations such as statute of limitations, procedural default, exhaustion, Teague v. Lane, if they surmount those hurdles, then the interests of vindicating the Constitution take precedence over the interests of finality.","start":1594.095,"stop":1625.055,"duration":30.96},{"text":"But if those procedural hurdles have not been met, and the defendant did not bring his claim in accordance with the procedures that are set out, then society is entitled to take that conviction as conclusively final, and any further remedy that would be available would have to come from the executive branch--","start":1625.055,"stop":1644.319,"duration":19.26}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you make that argument even if it's a Gideon violation?","start":1644.319,"stop":1647.042,"duration":2.72},{"text":"In other words, say that it's a final sentencing, the defendant had either no counsel or inadequate counsel, and didn't learn that there was a Gideon violation before and he'd already served his sentence for the crime where there was the Gideon violation, could he raise that or not?","start":1647.042,"stop":1661.466,"duration":14.42}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Under this Court's decision in Custis he may at the Federal sentencing raise it, and I--","start":1661.466,"stop":1666.689,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, not at the Federal sentencing.","start":1666.689,"stop":1668.038,"duration":1.35},{"text":"Say he gets sentence, and then by mistake the sentencing judge relies on a prior State conviction which was invalid because there was a Gideon violation, but nobody called that to the attention of the court.","start":1668.038,"stop":1679.246,"duration":11.21}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--That would be a procedural default, Justice Stevens, and I think it would bar the defendant from coming back even if there were otherwise a right to come back under applicable procedure.","start":1679.246,"stop":1689.58,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that be true even if the sentence had not been served where there was a Gideon violation?","start":1689.58,"stop":1694.147,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"The sentence of the... the underlying conviction--","start":1694.147,"stop":1698.049,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"This would always have to have been served, wouldn't it?","start":1698.049,"stop":1699.059,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, if the underlying conviction sentence had not been served, then the defendant's remedy would be to go back into the jurisdiction that entered it and see if he can comply with--","start":1699.059,"stop":1707.822,"duration":8.76}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"He couldn't then go in on a 2255 and call that to the court's attention and get relief, in your view?","start":1707.822,"stop":1707.822,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think so, Justice Stevens, because he has the right to do that under Custis at the Federal sentencing proceeding itself, and the failure to bring that claim at a timely point in the proceeding, when it is available, would constitute a default, and then he would be left with the argument--","start":1707.822,"stop":1730.33,"duration":22.51}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Even if he had... even if it was inadequate assistance of counsel?","start":1730.33,"stop":1732.846,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, inadequate assistance of counsel isn't even permitted to be brought under this Court's decision in Custis with respect to the underlying conviction.","start":1732.846,"stop":1742.394,"duration":9.55},{"text":"With respect to the conviction that... the Federal conviction that was entered, ineffective assistance of counsel claims typically are not brought in the original sentencing court that imposed the conviction because the defendant typically has the same counsel and because the facts haven't been developed, and therefore there is no procedural default typically in bringing an ineffective assistance claim directed to the Federal conviction in a section 2255 proceeding.","start":1742.394,"stop":1769.507,"duration":27.11},{"text":"But as to the underlying enhancement conviction, which is what we are talking about here, petitioner is saying that I suffered from ineffective assistance of counsel with respect to a 1978 robbery conviction that is now being used to enhance my 1992 Federal sentence, and I should have the right, on 2255, to litigate that 16-year-old, or 19-year-old claim, and we submit that the Court's decision in Custis says you can't do that at the Federal sentencing and you therefore cannot do that on the 2255 proceeding.","start":1769.507,"stop":1805.202,"duration":35.69}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but it's the therefore part that I guess is giving us all the trouble, and the reason it's giving me trouble is, number 1... of course, I was a dissenter in Custis, so maybe I'm looking for trouble--","start":1805.202,"stop":1816.427,"duration":11.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laughter]","start":1816.427,"stop":1816.602,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--but the Court in... the majority in Custis left the question open whether there could be another means of challenge other than the challenge at the Federal sentencing proceeding as such.","start":1816.602,"stop":1830.204,"duration":13.6},{"text":"And number 2, textually, what the petitioner wants to do can be fitted within the terms of 2255, and the issue I guess boils... so I think it's... I don't think Custis is controlling, and what the issue boils down to for me is this.","start":1830.204,"stop":1850.935,"duration":20.73},{"text":"I will... I accept your argument that the balance struck on the issues of finality and fairness require a point at which so far as the service of the original sentence, the '78 sentence in your example is concerned, the litigation has got to stop.","start":1850.935,"stop":1874.254,"duration":23.32},{"text":"But it seems to me that that balance is entirely different when you get into the subsequent proceeding in which, for example, what is at stake in the finality fairness argument is not, say, a sentence of 5 years or 10 years as under the first conviction, whatever it was, but a sentence potentially of life, and when suddenly the stakes change that radically in the Federal proceeding, then the old finality fairness balance simply doesn't apply any more because the terms have changed, and when the terms change radically, as they have here, why isn't it possible to reassess that balance and say, okay, now, even though you couldn't litigate for State purposes, you can litigate for Federal purposes?","start":1874.254,"stop":1926.949,"duration":52.7}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"The fundamental problem with that, Justice Souter, is that those same interests are fully at stake in the Custis situation itself.","start":1926.949,"stop":1933.784,"duration":6.84},{"text":"When this Court said--","start":1933.784,"stop":1935.429,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, but Custis... that may be true, but number 1, Custis depended in part on a statutory construction reason. They looked at the text of the sentencing enhancement statute and, number 2, Custis left this question open.","start":1935.429,"stop":1951.877,"duration":16.45},{"text":"The Court said--","start":1951.877,"stop":1952.884,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--If I could address that--","start":1952.884,"stop":1953.402,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--we're not telling you what we'll do in this subsequent situation, but they left it open.","start":1953.402,"stop":1958.315,"duration":4.91}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--That actually is not the question that the Court left open in Custis, Justice Souter.","start":1958.315,"stop":1962.32,"duration":4},{"text":"What the Court left open in Custis is the following scenario.","start":1962.32,"stop":1966.162,"duration":3.84},{"text":"Take Custis himself.","start":1966.162,"stop":1967.799,"duration":1.64},{"text":"After Custis is sentenced, the question that was raised in Custis was, could he then go back to the State court that had entered the enhancement conviction and obtain a judgment that that conviction was constitutionally invalid, and then come back to the Federal sentencing court and apply for reopening of his Federal sentence, and the crucial difference between that scenario and the scenario that's presented here is that the litigation over the validity of that sentence would take place in the State court.","start":1967.799,"stop":1998.692,"duration":30.89}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, you're entirely right, but didn't... I don't have it in front of me.","start":1998.692,"stop":2001.793,"duration":3.1},{"text":"Didn't the Court also refer to the possibility of litigation on Federal habeas?","start":2001.793,"stop":2006.454,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Litigation on Federal habeas corpus that attacked the State sentence.","start":2006.454,"stop":2010.752,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, but the only basis on which there could be Federal habeas litigation would be Federal habeas litigation in connection with the later Federal sentence, even though the subject of that litigation might be, or would be the validity of the earlier State sentence--","start":2010.752,"stop":2026.527,"duration":15.78}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think that that is--","start":2026.527,"stop":2027.896,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--and therefore it seems to me this was left open.","start":2027.896,"stop":2029.325,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I don't think that that's what the opinion says, because it talks about Custis having been in custody still on his State sentences.","start":2029.325,"stop":2036.509,"duration":7.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The last sentence of the opinion says, may attack his State sentence in Maryland or through a Federal habeas review.","start":2036.509,"stop":2041.115,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2041.115,"stop":2041.368,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2041.368,"stop":2041.818,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"And Federal habeas review is Federal review under 2254--","start":2041.818,"stop":2045.576,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Four, right.","start":2045.576,"stop":2046.09,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--that attacks the State sentence.","start":2046.09,"stop":2047.217,"duration":1.13},{"text":"This is a case under section 2255, attacking the constitutionality of the Federal sentence.","start":2047.217,"stop":2054.083,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did--","start":2054.083,"stop":2054.467,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"The necessary--","start":2054.467,"stop":2055.684,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Didn't we confine it to 2254?","start":2055.684,"stop":2057.846,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--The language says, I think accurately, just what Justice Stevens read, and I would interpret Federal habeas review in that context to mean Federal review under 2254 attacking the prior State sentence.","start":2057.846,"stop":2076.097,"duration":18.25}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly does include that.","start":2076.097,"stop":2077.206,"duration":1.11},{"text":"I don't know that it was limited.","start":2077.206,"stop":2078.362,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"If it were not limited to that, it would be odd to say that the defendant could then come and apply for reopening of this Federal sentence, because that's exactly what section 2255 is all about.","start":2078.362,"stop":2089.447,"duration":11.09},{"text":"It is saying there's something wrong with the Federal sentence that was imposed, and we know from Custis--","start":2089.447,"stop":2096.17,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"But the reason may be the textual reason in Custis, going to the text of the enhancement statute itself.","start":2096.17,"stop":2102.935,"duration":6.76},{"text":"It may be that we wanted sentencing, Congress wanted sentencing to be clean and simple and leaving any later attack to be worked out afterwards.","start":2102.935,"stop":2113.793,"duration":10.86},{"text":"In other words, get him shut away and then let him litigate as long as he wants to.","start":2113.793,"stop":2118.284,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--But the theory behind section 2255 litigation in this case is that there was a constitutional violation at the Federal sentencing.","start":2118.284,"stop":2126.168,"duration":7.88}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2126.168,"stop":2126.836,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Because sentence was imposed based on a conviction that, although facially valid and never set aside by any court, might be unreliable if one took the time to unpack the claim that petitioner is now making and get the records and litigate it and determine whether it's valid or not, and the Custis court held there is no constitutional violation in imposing sentence without adjudicating that claim and, further, by leaving open the question that we've been discussing, the Court made clear that it's not inherently indispensable that there be any place left to litigate a claim that is based on a conviction that is 16 years old in this case, 19 years old, that the two convictions the petitioner is raising.","start":2126.836,"stop":2168.633,"duration":41.8}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's assume, though... and I realize you don't concede this, of course, but assume that Custis did leave open the possibility of this litigation.","start":2168.633,"stop":2177.825,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Would you go back to the, we'll say the balance argument?","start":2177.825,"stop":2183.638,"duration":5.81},{"text":"My point is that the balance between finality and fairness changes radically when you go from the limited jeopardy of imprisonment under the State conviction to the potentiality here of life imprisonment, and if the balance is that radically affected, why shouldn't there be, for due process purposes, an opportunity to litigate at the Federal level, even though the State proceeding is past and final for State purposes?","start":2183.638,"stop":2213.667,"duration":30.03}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Souter, I think the fundamental answer to that question goes back to the interests in finality that have been struck in this Court's postconviction jurisprudence generally.","start":2213.667,"stop":2224.302,"duration":10.64},{"text":"There is a recognition that there are fundamental interests in having an unconstitutional conviction overturned, but they are counterbalanced by other interests such as the fairness and reliability of the adjudication of that claim.","start":2224.302,"stop":2237.595,"duration":13.29},{"text":"Now, here we are talking about a claim by petitioner that when he entered his guilty plea 16 years ago and 19 years ago he wasn't adequately informed about one of the elements of the offense and therefore, he says, he didn't enter a knowing and voluntary guilty plea.","start":2237.595,"stop":2252.941,"duration":15.35},{"text":"Now, that's the kind of claim that can routinely be made on direct appeal or upon an immediate post conviction attack, and it's made with the State that entered the judgment as a party, and the State can come back and say we have access to these records, they're very easy to determine, you can see that the judge went over him, the various elements, or his lawyer counseled him about the various elements of the crime and the court can reach a reliable adjudication promptly on whether that conviction is valid.","start":2252.941,"stop":2280.662,"duration":27.72},{"text":"A defendant who doesn't challenge his guilty plea in that fashion at the time that it's available to do so is essentially saying, I struck a deal with the Government, the deal allows me perhaps to reduce my time of imprisonment compared to what it would have been if I had gone to trial and lost, as I probably would have been, would have lost, therefore I'm going to enter a guilty plea and establish finality, and I'm not going to take an appeal, because if I appeal and win at this juncture I'll probably be back right in the position that I started in, namely, facing a trial and a potentially longer sentence.","start":2280.662,"stop":2312.301,"duration":31.64}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's perfectly fair for due process purposes or any others, on any other fairness standard, to hold the prisoner to that bargain.","start":2312.301,"stop":2320.548,"duration":8.25},{"text":"He knew what the terms were.","start":2320.548,"stop":2322.163,"duration":1.62},{"text":"The trouble is now, the terms have changed, and it's not only very difficult to litigate this later, but it's also very difficult to stay in prison for life, and when the terms have changed, the calculus that says, or that said in the first instance it's fair to hold you to your bargain, doesn't apply any more, because the terms have changed.","start":2322.163,"stop":2346.342,"duration":24.18}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"But the risk that he faced, Justice Souter, was one that he either knew actually or should have known at the time that he entered that plea.","start":2346.342,"stop":2354.068,"duration":7.73}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, let's... I understand that argument, too, and I just don't see how it is sound. The truth is, in the real world, prisoners, when they enter these guilty pleas, are not thinking of the possibility of life in prison 25 years later for a crime that hasn't been committed yet.","start":2354.068,"stop":2373.913,"duration":19.84},{"text":"I mean, I just don't think that that is realistic, to say that he knew or should have known that this could happen.","start":2373.913,"stop":2379.617,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, apart from the fact that the Court in Nichols v. United States said that it's the kind of thing that prisoners do know when they're sentenced, that if they're seen back again they're going to face more serious consequences from it--","start":2379.617,"stop":2393.228,"duration":13.61}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"They... more serious consequences, yes, but this is a serious consequence of a different order of magnitude.","start":2393.228,"stop":2401.691,"duration":8.46}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think that recidivism statutes are among the most common kind of statutes in the criminal justice world.","start":2401.691,"stop":2406.743,"duration":5.05},{"text":"All 50 States have them.","start":2406.743,"stop":2409.038,"duration":2.3},{"text":"The Federal Government has one.","start":2409.038,"stop":2410.558,"duration":1.52},{"text":"There's a great deal--","start":2410.558,"stop":2411.833,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, recidivism, yes, but we're... at least at this point in history we're living at a time when a great many prior convictions are being considered under three strikes laws--","start":2411.833,"stop":2420.981,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct.","start":2420.981,"stop":2421.433,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--let alone a Federal three strikes law which couldn't possibly have been in the contemplation of the people who entered the guilty pleas or suffered the convictions 25 years ago.","start":2421.433,"stop":2431.063,"duration":9.63}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but there has long been a tradition in this country of recidivism laws that fairly significantly escalated the potential sentence from some of the cases that I've seen from 5 years to 35 years, and these are convictions based on statutes that were enacted long before the current wave of three strikes statutes.","start":2431.063,"stop":2449.668,"duration":18.61}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I thought what we're concerned about are people who in 1972... something that appeared fairly minor to the individual who is convicted, he's told by somebody, go in and plead guilty, it's not going to be a big deal.","start":2449.668,"stop":2465.473,"duration":15.8},{"text":"He has no idea what he's doing.","start":2465.473,"stop":2467.492,"duration":2.02},{"text":"He doesn't get correct advice, and he goes in and he pleads guilty, and he was totally confused at the State proceeding.","start":2467.492,"stop":2474.315,"duration":6.82},{"text":"Now, that person is going to be in jail for life because of a later crime, although if you look at what happened it would be obviously unconstitutional, his earlier conviction.","start":2474.315,"stop":2487.546,"duration":13.23},{"text":"Now, that's the case we're worried about, and we get rid of the other cases through strict burden of proof rules, so all we have in front of us are those cases, and the question is, why shouldn't a person like that be able to demonstrate the obvious fact that that earlier conviction was obviously unconstitutional, and you give me the answer that Custis says no, but then we could just reply, well, that was because of the language of the statute.","start":2487.546,"stop":2513.802,"duration":26.26}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think--","start":2513.802,"stop":2515.321,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Here, although we're running around Robin's barn or something in some weird procedural way, better let him do it later than not at all.","start":2515.321,"stop":2515.321,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think the constitutional holding in Custis had anything to do with the language of the statutes.","start":2515.321,"stop":2527.965,"duration":12.64},{"text":"The Court concluded that the statute in Custis, which is the same statute at issue here, didn't authorize these kinds of challenges at the sentencing proceeding and it then went on to hold that neither did the Constitution.","start":2527.965,"stop":2539.153,"duration":11.19},{"text":"Now, petitioner's--","start":2539.153,"stop":2540.249,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"At the sentencing proceeding.","start":2540.249,"stop":2541.435,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, but there's nothing--","start":2541.435,"stop":2542.553,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But you could say, I guess... and I don't know how much of a stretch this would be.","start":2542.553,"stop":2546.549,"duration":4},{"text":"You could say, but this person who is obviously convicted unconstitutionally, and I'll underscore obviously, because I can get rid of the nonobvious cases through strict burdens of proof, all right, so he was obviously convicted unconstitutionally, that that person should have some forum somewhere in which to point that out before he's in prison for life.","start":2546.549,"stop":2569.047,"duration":22.5}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Justice Breyer, I accept that you've attempted to carve out the category of obvious unconstitutionality from what we're dealing with in this realm, but I submit that as a matter of real life litigation it doesn't exist.","start":2569.047,"stop":2582.808,"duration":13.76},{"text":"What you in fact get in the vast majority of cases are records just like this one.","start":2582.808,"stop":2588.711,"duration":5.9},{"text":"The prisoner comes in--","start":2588.711,"stop":2590.35,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"The vast majority, fine, but we also have a few cases where it was like somebody had robbed a chicken coop, you know, when he was 18 years old, and now 12 years later this chicken coop has come back to put him in prison for life, so there are also at least a few cases where you think maybe he didn't get very good advice the first time.","start":2590.35,"stop":2590.35,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Any constitutional rule that says you can do this but only when it's really obvious is going to lead to the same sorts of burdens of litigation of whether it falls into that category or not, and it's going to require the Government, when confronted with one of these things, to do exactly what the Court recognized in Custis was an extremely burdensome and usually unproductive exercise of running round and trying to find the prosecutor, the judge, the defense lawyer, the probation officer who were part of the original sentencing proceeding, which could go back decades, and attempting to reconstruct--","start":2590.35,"stop":2641.628,"duration":51.28}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's the prisoner's problem.","start":2641.628,"stop":2642.868,"duration":1.24},{"text":"The Government doesn't have to do that.","start":2642.868,"stop":2644.714,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, it is the Government's problem, because the prisoner comes in with an affidavit that says, I was there, and I'm going to swear out as a factual matter no one ever told me that aiding and abetting liability required that I join in this venture as if it were something that I intended to succeed.","start":2644.714,"stop":2660.112,"duration":15.4},{"text":"All I thought is that if I was present and I knew about the bank robbery, that was enough for the conviction.","start":2660.112,"stop":2665.489,"duration":5.38},{"text":"That is petitioner's claim right here.","start":2665.489,"stop":2667.781,"duration":2.29},{"text":"He's filed an affidavit, he's sworn it out under oath, and for the Government to sit back and say to the sentencing court, well, judge, he has a strong interest in this and this was 20 years ago, you shouldn't believe him, is really more than can be expected from us.","start":2667.781,"stop":2681.433,"duration":13.65},{"text":"We need to respond factually.","start":2681.433,"stop":2683.114,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, you've got a case that has facts that are very favorable to the Government generally, but some of these cases are much closer, like the Seventh Circuit case where the evidence was really quite disturbing about whether the person actually received a fair proceeding, but you would apply the same rule regardless of how strong the proof is.","start":2683.114,"stop":2697.723,"duration":14.61}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Justice Stevens.","start":2697.723,"stop":2699.001,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"And regardless of how serious the violation is, unless it's a Gideon violation.","start":2699.001,"stop":2702.581,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, and I think that that is the line that the Court drew in Custis, and it essentially says--","start":2702.581,"stop":2706.819,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but Custis really was a holding on the meaning of 924(e) on the sentencing proceedings.","start":2706.819,"stop":2710.988,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Custis was a holding first on the meaning of 924(e) and then on what the Constitution required of a sentencing judge, and it held a sentencing judge may accept a facially valid--","start":2710.988,"stop":2721.655,"duration":10.67}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2721.655,"stop":2722.144,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--conviction that has never been set aside, other than--","start":2722.144,"stop":2724.828,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"And of course, one reason that's permissible is that normally there's a second chance to prove what really happened.","start":2724.828,"stop":2729.74,"duration":4.91},{"text":"That's part of the answer--","start":2729.74,"stop":2731.765,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":2731.765,"stop":2731.918,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--given in that very case, that they... there is this other open question.","start":2731.918,"stop":2735.525,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--There are normally other chances for a defendant to attack his prior conviction, the direct appeal from the conviction, postconviction review in the State, and postconviction review federally.","start":2735.525,"stop":2744.991,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That was true in Custis itself, wasn't it?","start":2744.991,"stop":2747.152,"duration":2.16},{"text":"He could have gone back to the State court?","start":2747.152,"stop":2748.999,"duration":1.85},{"text":"Yes.","start":2748.999,"stop":2750.102,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2750.102,"stop":2750.56,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"It said he could have gone to Maryland or on 2254 review--","start":2750.56,"stop":2755.113,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2755.113,"stop":2755.58,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--of the Maryland conviction.","start":2755.58,"stop":2756.66,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, and the Court didn't say that this is an indispensable prerequisite of a valid Federal sentence. What it said was, the Federal sentencing court can look at the State judgment and say, on its face there's no Gideon problem here, we're not required to entertain other constitutional challenges.","start":2756.66,"stop":2773.194,"duration":16.53}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr.--","start":2773.194,"stop":2773.604,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"If some other court wants to entertain them, that's to be presented to that court.","start":2773.604,"stop":2777.994,"duration":4.39},{"text":"The rendering court--","start":2777.994,"stop":2779.406,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Mr. Dreeben, I don't know why we focus upon what the expectation of the defendant was at the time he pleaded guilty, as opposed to what his expectation was at the time he committed the later crime.","start":2779.406,"stop":2795.17,"duration":15.76},{"text":"Do you think it would be unconstitutional for a State to say that anyone who has a prior conviction on the record, all right, that has been obtained in any manner so long as Gideon has been complied with, anyone who has that on his record who commits a later crime gets a longer sentence?","start":2795.17,"stop":2820.124,"duration":24.95}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, I don't think that's unconstitutional.","start":2820.124,"stop":2823.268,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"He knows what the rules are when he commits the later crime.","start":2823.268,"stop":2825.98,"duration":2.71},{"text":"He knows he pleaded guilty of the former crime.","start":2825.98,"stop":2828.147,"duration":2.17},{"text":"He knows that anyone who has pleaded guilty to a former crime will get a longer sentence.","start":2828.147,"stop":2833.522,"duration":5.38},{"text":"Isn't that the expectation that we should be concerned about?","start":2833.522,"stop":2836.248,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"That is a, an expectation that the prisoner can have that the laws give him notice that that's what the laws are intended to do.","start":2836.248,"stop":2842.628,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But then it's your view, I take it, that even if the prior conviction were set aside in State proceedings or Federal proceedings, that that would not justify a reduction in the Federal sentence?","start":2842.628,"stop":2852.871,"duration":10.24}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Stevens--","start":2852.871,"stop":2854.213,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that your view?","start":2854.213,"stop":2854.587,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--It is a view that the Government has taken in the lower courts.","start":2854.587,"stop":2858.147,"duration":3.56},{"text":"We have lost it in the six circuits that have considered it.","start":2858.147,"stop":2861.2,"duration":3.05},{"text":"We're currently rethinking what our position is on that issue.","start":2861.2,"stop":2864.576,"duration":3.38},{"text":"That issue is a quite distinct issue from this one.","start":2864.576,"stop":2867.379,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2867.379,"stop":2868.07,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Because in that situation the Federal court, instead of saying, I have a facially valid conviction in front of me and I have a defendant who says there's something wrong with it but he's never done anything about it, the Federal court in this latter class of cases has a conviction that it previously relied on and said, this is a reliable indication that you are a more serious offender, and it turns out that a later State court judgment may have set it aside on constitutional grounds that fundamentally call into question reliability.","start":2868.07,"stop":2895.226,"duration":27.16},{"text":"That's a distinguishable scenario from this situation, and the outcome there does not control the outcome here.","start":2895.226,"stop":2901.039,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree, but apparently Justice Scalia would not, is my point.","start":2901.039,"stop":2903.582,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think Justice Scalia is referring to a statute that was premised on the following theory.","start":2903.582,"stop":2907.357,"duration":3.78},{"text":"If you know you have a conviction on the books and you are not deterred from the... by committing another crime, notwithstanding the fact that you know that your sentenced will be enhanced, the question is, is that constitutional apart from Gideon violations.","start":2907.357,"stop":2922.182,"duration":14.82},{"text":"My answer to that is yes, but I don't actually think that's the sentencing theory that was adopted in section 924(e).","start":2922.182,"stop":2930.237,"duration":8.06}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a statutory question, though, and not a constitutional question, whether the statute was of the sort that I--","start":2930.237,"stop":2937.419,"duration":7.18}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2937.419,"stop":2938.631,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--That I described or not.","start":2938.631,"stop":2938.9,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct, and if it were of the sort, I would submit that it's constitutional, but the question is, is it of that sort.","start":2938.9,"stop":2945.219,"duration":6.32}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2945.219,"stop":2946.013,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"And I think the answer to it is not.","start":2946.013,"stop":2947.12,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But if you say that it would be constitutional if it were of that sort, then isn't it a fortiori true that what the defendant is complaining about here is likewise constitutional?","start":2947.12,"stop":2959.891,"duration":12.77}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it's a fortiori, Justice Scalia, although I do think our position is a fortiori from Custis, and the reason I think they're distinct is, the theory of the sentencing statute that you have posited is deterrence, and the theory of the recidivist sentencing statute, that is 924(e), and of most recidivist statutes, is reliability of a prior conviction which shows that this defendant is a more serious offender because he has committed crimes in the past which aggravate the current offense, and therefore this individual warrants greater incapacitation as a matter of protecting the public because he's clearly not learning but is going on to commit offense after offense after offense.","start":2959.891,"stop":3005.462,"duration":45.57}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I recognize what we said in Custis, but is there any other structural or fundamental area, other than Gideon, that we should recognize... the judge was bribed--","start":3005.462,"stop":3017.129,"duration":11.67}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the United States took the position in Custis that Gideon error belonged to a very small class of fundamental errors, and the other error that we identified in Custis was the error that you identified, Justice Kennedy, of an error that really deprives the sentencing court of the character of a court that could render a fair judgment.","start":3017.129,"stop":3043.143,"duration":26.01}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--But that's not subsumed in the category of facially valid, is it?","start":3043.143,"stop":3047.596,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because this Court in Custis didn't agree with the position of the Government and held that Gideon violations are unique.","start":3047.596,"stop":3054.736,"duration":7.14},{"text":"They are unique not only because they have such a pervasive impact on the fairness of the proceeding, but they are also unique in that they are fairly easy to discern from the judgment role or from a motion accompanying the judgment role, and the Court relied on the consideration of administrative ease as well as of the character of the error in defining what you could do when confronted with a recidivist enhancement and a prior conviction that is challenged on constitutional grounds, and so long as the Court adheres to that line, I think that the interest of the State in ensuring that its judgment carries usual force and effect are just as strong at the Federal sentencing proceeding as they are on 2255.","start":3054.736,"stop":3098.536,"duration":43.8},{"text":"The State--","start":3098.536,"stop":3099.402,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But you're... but you are leaving open the possibility, say somebody in this position, there's a quorum nobis proceeding in the State, gets it knocked out under State law, you're saying that that's the situation the Government is rethinking whether then, if you succeed, even way out of time, to get it knocked out at the State court, could you then come back to Federal court on a 2255 and say, now the State has knocked this out?","start":3099.402,"stop":3126.855,"duration":27.45}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's correct, Justice Ginsburg.","start":3126.855,"stop":3129.138,"duration":2.28},{"text":"That's the question that we're revisiting after our litigation track record in the lower courts, and it's not presented in this case because petitioner did not do that, and almost undoubtedly would be out of time to do that today, and quorum nobis is not apparently available in California, and our fundamental submission is, that was the chance that he had.","start":3129.138,"stop":3150.072,"duration":20.93},{"text":"Whatever procedures the rendering court provides and post conviction review provides of the underlying conviction are sufficient for constitutional purposes absent a Gideon error when the Federal sentencing court is imposing a recidivist sentence.","start":3150.072,"stop":3166.462,"duration":16.39},{"text":"If the Court has no further questions--","start":3166.462,"stop":3168.988,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Dreeben.","start":3168.988,"stop":3170.175,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Michael R. Dreeben","textObjs":[{"text":"--Thank you.","start":3170.175,"stop":3168.988,"duration":-1.19}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Tanaka, you have 7 minutes remaining.","start":3168.988,"stop":3173.155,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd first like to address the question of what Custis left open.","start":3173.155,"stop":3180.018,"duration":6.86},{"text":"We've been talking about the sentence at issue, and it ends, if... we recognize... and this is at page 497 of the Custis decision.","start":3180.018,"stop":3188.956,"duration":8.94},{"text":"We recognize, however, that Custis, who is still in custody for purposes of State convictions, at the time of this Federal sentencing under 924(e) may attack a State sentence in Maryland or through a Federal habeas review, and then, importantly, after that the citation is just see Maleng v. Cook.","start":3188.956,"stop":3207.222,"duration":18.27},{"text":"Now, there are two things that suggest that what that left open was the possibility of reviewing the prior conviction as it enhanced the later sentence.","start":3207.222,"stop":3217.598,"duration":10.38},{"text":"First is that it says, or through a Federal habeas review, and second it says, it cites Maleng v. Cook.","start":3217.598,"stop":3224.065,"duration":6.47},{"text":"Now, what Maleng decided was that there was subject matter jurisdiction in a Federal habeas case where there was an expired conviction, and the petitioner in that case had attacked an expired conviction directly and what this Court said was, no, you couldn't attack that directly, but there was subject matter jurisdiction on habeas where that prior conviction was used to enhance a subsequent sentence.","start":3224.065,"stop":3249.78,"duration":25.72},{"text":"So that strongly suggests that the remedy that this Court left open in Custis is akin to what exactly is at issue here and that is, a 2255 remedy, by its very terms, allows the petitioner to attack the constitutionality of that prior State conviction, as it was used to enhance his Federal sentence.","start":3249.78,"stop":3268.924,"duration":19.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Maleng, though, was directed just to whether or not he was in custody.","start":3268.924,"stop":3272.265,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, whether he was in custody on the subsequent sentence, but it suggests that they would entertain attack on the prior conviction through the custody of the subsequent sentence and conviction.","start":3272.265,"stop":3286.623,"duration":14.36},{"text":"The other point I wanted to make is, the Solicitor General mentioned that there was a fairness finality balance here, and that this changes where the conviction, as in this case, is so old, but that fails to recognize that the finality interests where the conviction is used in a subsequent proceeding are not the same.","start":3286.623,"stop":3314.421,"duration":27.8},{"text":"In fact, they're not even close to the same, where we're challenging the challenges to that State conviction directly, and that is because this Court's jurisprudence in many of those 2254 cases regarding finality posits the rationale that the State judgment is a final one, and we don't want to intrude in the State process.","start":3314.421,"stop":3338.68,"duration":24.26},{"text":"That is, we don't want to release this person from custody.","start":3338.68,"stop":3342.394,"duration":3.71},{"text":"We don't want to make the State retry this man.","start":3342.394,"stop":3344.367,"duration":1.97},{"text":"We don't want to intrude in the State process.","start":3344.367,"stop":3348.159,"duration":3.79},{"text":"In this case, again, that interest is almost nonexistent.","start":3348.159,"stop":3353.445,"duration":5.29},{"text":"If a Federal sentencing court granted a 2255, there is no impact on that State court judgment.","start":3353.445,"stop":3360.426,"duration":6.98},{"text":"So it really boils down to a question of, is there a remedy for someone who is going to face a potential life term--","start":3360.426,"stop":3370.516,"duration":10.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"May I just question your last conclusion?","start":3370.516,"stop":3373.136,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Supposing he had not... he was still in State custody on parole or something of that kind, would not then the Federal 2255 have an impact on the State's interest in finality?","start":3373.136,"stop":3383.167,"duration":10.03}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm not sure it would--","start":3383.167,"stop":3386.016,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems hard to imagine the Federal judge would conclude the State's conviction was invalid, and therefore nothing would happen in the State proceedings after that.","start":3386.016,"stop":3393.839,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, certainly the Federal court would have no conclusive effect on any subsequent State court proceeding, and whatever persuasive value I imagine that the State court could take it for what it was worth, but I don't know that it would necessarily intrude on the State court proceeding.","start":3393.839,"stop":3412.43,"duration":18.59},{"text":"So basically what's at issue, then, is do we allow 2255, which by its fine language provides a remedy where the sentence is unconstitutional, do we close that door on the basis of considerations that aren't at issue in this case, or do we allow someone who's facing a life sentence to litigate the validity, and in some cases it's going to be obvious, of prior convictions that don't reliably indicate his guilt and, as the Solicitor General said, the whole purpose between the armed career criminal act is incapacitation, or--","start":3412.43,"stop":3451.817,"duration":39.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, in this case, Mr. Tanaka, it's a guilty plea, so you don't have any real question of whether there's a record to show that he did it or didn't do it, because you don't get that sort of a record with a guilty plea.","start":3451.817,"stop":3464.593,"duration":12.78}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's correct, Your Honor, and so the issue then would be, does this record reliably reflect his guilt, reviewing the record that's presented on the guilty plea, and that would be an issue for the Federal district court to decide on remand.","start":3464.593,"stop":3480.222,"duration":15.63},{"text":"If it decided that indeed there's enough evidence here that we have no question that he was guilty and there's a reliable indication of that, then I suppose he's out of court, but the point is, he needs to have that opportunity.","start":3480.222,"stop":3493.348,"duration":13.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's very difficult, as pointed out in the briefs, when you're dealing with convictions that are 16 and 19 years old, to go back and show exactly what happened at a guilty plea.","start":3493.348,"stop":3504.412,"duration":11.06}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll grant that, but again I think that that concern is addressed by placing the burden of proof on the petitioner, which... where it lies, and if the sentencing court doesn't find that persuasive, then--","start":3504.412,"stop":3518.321,"duration":13.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but as Mr. Dreeben pointed out, your client can simply file an affidavit saying that, you know, I wasn't fully advised of what was going on, and then it's up to the Government to come back.","start":3518.321,"stop":3518.321,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"It's very difficult for someone who is facing that kind of an affidavit to simply say, well, disbelieve this guy.","start":3518.321,"stop":3537.267,"duration":18.95},{"text":"You want to collect information showing that he should be disbelieved.","start":3537.267,"stop":3541.665,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"--And to the extent that's possible I'm sure the Government will do that.","start":3541.665,"stop":3546.135,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, with great administrative burden.","start":3546.135,"stop":3548.371,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"G. Michael Tanaka","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the fact is there just aren't that many of these cases, but that's a price that we need to pay in order to make sure that people aren't unjustly--","start":3548.371,"stop":3558.163,"duration":9.79}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but there comes a point when the Government should be entitled to say, this is the way the cookie crumbles.","start":3558.163,"stop":3563.013,"duration":4.85},{"text":"You bought into this, and you're stuck with it.","start":3563.013,"stop":3565.271,"duration":2.26},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3565.271,"stop":3566.512,"duration":1.24},{"text":"That's not a question.","start":3566.512,"stop":3567.173,"duration":0.66},{"text":"Well, the case is submitted.","start":3567.173,"stop":3576.807,"duration":9.63}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Rehnquist Court","arguedOn":"Jan 8, 2001","petitioner":"Daniels","respondent":"United States","docket":"99-9136","citation":"532 US 374 (2001)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/532/374","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Apr 25, 2001"}